==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: paradoxism
<hw>par"a*dox`ism</hw> <pr>(p⟦acr⟧r"⟦adot⟧*d⟦ocr⟧ks`⟦icr⟧z'm)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>paradox</ets> + <ets>-ism</ets>. <fu>ca.
1980</fu>]</ety> <def>An avant-garde movement in literature, art, and
philosophy, based on excessive used of antitheses, antinomies,
contradictions, oxymorons, and paradoxes.</def> <au>Charles Le
(https://web.archive.org/web/20091018202429/http://www.geocities.com/charlestle/paradoxism.html)</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note> Paradoxism originated in Romania in the 1980s as a way of
protesting against a closed society and a totalitarian regime. It is
based on an excessive use of antimonies, antitheses, contradictions,
oxymorons, and paradoxes. It was set up and led by the writer
<person>Florentin Smarandache</person> in the 1980's, who said:
⟦ldquo⟧The goal is the enlargement of the artistic sphere through
non-artistic elements⟦rdquo⟧.⟦br⟧
One example of such a paradox is the two-line poem:⟦br⟧
Even if he didn't⟦br⟧
He did⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
A free eBook on "Paradoxism and Postmodernism" can be downloaded from
https://zenodo.org/record/8865#.YIWBb_kvBhE</note>.⟦br⟧
[<source>Charles Le</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Paradoxology</ent>⟦br⟧
